This aligns directly with the hypothesis that discount campaigns suppress AOV via a bargain-hunter effect. It also falls squarely within the organization-specific expected magnitude of 10-25% lower on campaign days, landing near the upper end of that range. The sample sizes (1,834 vs 484 orders) are large enough to make the observed gap unlikely to be noise, though the analysis lacks a formal significance test or decomposition by product/customer mix that could rule out confounders (e.g., campaigns attracting more new customers or cheaper seasonal SKUs).

Overall, the direction, magnitude, and sample support all point to the hypothesis being confirmed.", "verdict": "supported", "evidence_summary": "Campaign-day AOV (9,693) is ~23% below non-campaign AOV (12,617), matching the hypothesized bargain-hunter suppression within the expected 10-25% range."}
